02:57.975 --> 02:58.907
What we got?

02:58.976 --> 03:00.842
Danielle Zora, 22.

03:00.911 --> 03:01.955
Neighbor found
her like this.

03:01.979 --> 03:03.578
OD?
She had a baggie on her.

03:03.647 --> 03:04.647
Looks like cocaine.

03:04.681 --> 03:06.481
Was she with anyone last night?

03:06.550 --> 03:08.461
Not that we've learned, but
we got her roommate downstairs.

03:08.485 --> 03:09.485
Gavin Schlenger.

03:11.588 --> 03:12.687
That him?

03:12.756 --> 03:14.656
Yeah.

03:19.463 --> 03:20.395
Gavin?

03:20.464 --> 03:22.130
Detective Reagan.

03:22.199 --> 03:23.331
My partner Detective Baez.

03:23.400 --> 03:27.502
We understand you live here.
Yes.

03:27.571 --> 03:29.270
Any idea what Danielle
or who she was with?

03:29.339 --> 03:31.006
No, I-I don't have any idea.

03:31.074 --> 03:33.174
Was Danielle a
partier at all?

03:33.243 --> 03:34.642
I mean, she like
to do drugs?

03:34.711 --> 03:36.644
I mean, not more
than the next person,

03:36.713 --> 03:39.014
but it wasn't
uncommon in our crowd.

03:39.082 --> 03:40.315
What do you mean, your crowd?

03:40.384 --> 03:46.888
We're both artists. Um,
or she was an artist, anyways.

03:46.957 --> 03:49.090
she's, like, the last one
I expected to,

03:49.159 --> 03:50.492
to take it to that level.

04:02.439 --> 04:04.305
Two more, Jimmy?

04:07.911 --> 04:10.812
You know how I know
I'm still an optimist?

04:10.881 --> 04:11.980
No, how?

04:12.049 --> 04:15.550
When I get a message
that you're back in town,

04:15.619 --> 04:18.053
I don't go,
"This can't be good."

04:18.120 --> 04:19.154
Uh-huh.

04:19.221 --> 04:22.223
I go, "Oh, good.
Lenny's back."

04:25.395 --> 04:26.706
Well, thanks
for coming out, Frankie.

04:26.730 --> 04:28.730
- Sure.
- How's the family?

04:28.799 --> 04:31.866
All good. Jamie's
getting married.

04:31.935 --> 04:32.935
To a cop.

04:32.969 --> 04:34.169
Sweet. Congratulations.

04:34.984 --> 04:37.572
Okay. What?

04:37.641 --> 04:38.473
What?

04:38.497 --> 04:41.377
The Lenny I know, that's
an opening to bust balls.

04:41.378 --> 04:43.411
No, no, I mean it.
I'm-I'm happy for him.

04:43.480 --> 04:45.680
- Really.
- Thank you.

04:47.884 --> 04:48.817
Thanks, Jimmy.

04:48.885 --> 04:50.318
To family.

04:50.387 --> 04:51.953
To family. Okay.

04:58.562 --> 05:01.830
I was contacted
by a journalist who's, uh,

05:01.898 --> 05:03.932
doing a profile of
Joey "The Elephant" Nocerino

05:04.000 --> 05:05.233
for <i>The New Yorker.</i>

05:05.302 --> 05:08.937
Boy... there's a name I
haven't heard for a while.

05:09.005 --> 05:10.216
Well, that's because
the old dirtbag's

05:10.240 --> 05:12.073
been locked up
for 20 years.

05:12.142 --> 05:14.042
Forgotten but not gone.

05:14.111 --> 05:16.344
What's the story?

05:16.413 --> 05:17.790
Oh, it's another
<i>Goodfellas</i> knockoff

05:17.814 --> 05:19.247
starring Nocerino as Henry Hill.

05:19.316 --> 05:21.116
Says he remembers everything.

05:21.184 --> 05:24.018
"An Elephant Never Forgets,"
that's the title of the piece.

05:24.087 --> 05:25.720
Where's this going?

05:25.789 --> 05:29.791
He says I looked the other way
on some drug shipments

05:29.860 --> 05:32.594
when I was working narcotics
back in the '80s.

05:32.662 --> 05:35.063
Says I let some
of his rats run.

05:35.132 --> 05:38.099
The writer's got to get your
side of the story, right?

05:38.168 --> 05:39.501
Well...
What the hell?

05:39.569 --> 05:41.870
I gave my side
of the story.

05:41.938 --> 05:43.338
Well, then,
what's the problem?

05:45.108 --> 05:49.110
Problem is that what
Nocerino told him is true.

05:50.714 --> 05:52.647
Listen, I never
crossed the line

05:52.716 --> 05:54.249
when we were
partners, Frankie.

05:54.317 --> 05:55.717
I swear to God,
I never did that.

05:55.785 --> 05:56.951
But I just wanted to...

05:57.020 --> 06:00.054
give you a heads-up,
let you get ahead of it.

06:00.123 --> 06:02.357
Protect your house.

06:05.328 --> 06:08.596
And... say goodbye.

06:12.435 --> 06:14.102
I'm really sorry,
Frankie, I'm...

06:16.339 --> 06:20.842
I'm gonna
miss... this.

